* Score
5/5

* Strengths
- This work condenses down a decade's worth of knowledge of managing possibly the largest datacenters in the world into a concise paper
- The team took a wildly different route at the start of the project with the hypothesis that exploiting Moore's law by constantly using the
  newest cheap off-shelf merchant silicon will lead to the best result.
- They backed this up with a decade long of data and almost 3 magnitudes of bandwidth increase.
- Captures some of the future innovation in networking such as Software defined Networking by using a centralized control structure
- Covers almost all of the possible impediments one would encounter in deploying such a massive network down to the copper wiring challenges.
- Highlight the mistakes they made so that future works can avoid costly pitfalls

* Weaknesses

* Summary
This paper is about the evolution of Google's datacenter network.

** Motivation
- As traffic between servers on a datacenter increased there was need for the redesign of the network topologies
  used.
- The existing state of the art topology was limited by the size of the core switch used atop of the network and
  had scaling issues both in cost and performance
- The need of redundancy both in terms storage, compute and more important power demanded a equal distribution of
  bandwidth across servers.
- All of these factors lead to Google rethinking their network.

** Core tenets
The three main tenets of Google's approach are as follows

1. Clos Topology
2. Off-the shelf merchant silicon
3. Centralized control protocol


** Network Evolution

| Generation   | Biggest Change                                                |
|--------------+---------------------------------------------------------------|
| Firehose 1.0 | Changed to a clos topology. Used servers as switches          |
| Firehose 1.1 | Changed to use a custom built switch.                         |
|              | Redundant links to the aggregator which had redundancy itself |
| Watchtower   | Switched to traditional switch chassis using newer silicon.   |
|              | Bundling cables.                                              |
| Saturn       | Uses 24x10G silicon.                                          |
| Jupiter      | 40G silicon                                                   |


** Control Protocols
- Traditional spanning tree protocol will negate all the parallel path in order to prevent any loops. So Google had to use a different control system.
- Usually control protocols are designed so that switches can act autonomously to learn network changes and routing paths. But due to the nature of a datacenter
  the roles each switch take is not dynamic. It is largely static. So Google went with a Centralized Control Protocol called *Firepath*. The switches still
  communicated about links going down but the global data was obtained from a Firepath master.

* Review
- Well written in depth paper about creating one of the largest scale datacenter networks in the world. Captures all of the advances
  made in networking during that decade and how they adapted it. Serves as guide for future large scale endevors.
